  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>EVERQUEST : HIS RISE - CHAPTER 7</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><center><b>Chapter Seven</b><br><i>Miragul. The Crystal. Realizations.</i></center><p>
     The undead mage floated before them, his form still solidifying due to the call.  As his dark eyes gazed at those in his tunnel it’s decaying face grinned with some unknown delight.  The lich moved his hands to his chest and opened up his robe, exposing a ghastly sight, where something seemed to be missing there.  His dark fiery eyes set their gaze upon Malok.<p>
     Malok stood stunned from fear for a moment, before he realized what the next step was.  Lowering his breathing, as it had sped up due to the prior events, he turned to his comrades.  Motioning Barnok to bring him something.  Barnok reached into a gem encrusted pouch and retrieved a amulet.<p>  
     The amulet was golden with streaks of dark sapphires hung upon a silvered chain.  It was the lich’s phylactery, as their studies into it’s history had discovered.  Upon the lich’s lips grew a wide smile, the sight was almost maddening.  For he knew what was about to happen.  Yet, still the lich did not make any moves except to bob up and down upon the air, as he gently floated.<p>
     Malok took the amulet, and looked down at the speaking crystal.  The crystal didn’t speak or offer any advice.  Malok growled at it, and lifted up the tome off the ground from where he had set it during the entire event.  Painfully flipping through the book he found the spell which they had discussed before their trek set out.  Transfer of Souls, or so it was labeled.  As he looked over the spell, Miragul’s lich did the same, and slowly his smile faded, and his face turned into that of a lust.  A moment before it began to make unearthly gurgles of chuckles.  The gnoll leader paid no mind to those sound and began to recite the spell which was within the tome.  <p>
     "<i>Shronaknah zenolkka rolaga korintha,</i>" suddenly the cavern filled with air spinning violently around in circles about Malok as bright wisps of light shimmered into existence. Holding the amulet into the air he continued to recite the words, "<i>menoskkra senosro talo sentrunah!</i>"  Now swirls of darkness whipped up around him, revolving around the amulet.  Wisps of white light began to seep from the amulet and mix in with the darkness. <p> 
     Now even the lich’s lips were moving as if reciting their own incantation.  Abruptly the blackness disappeared and only the white light remained, swirling.  The lich began to speak, his voice horrifying sending many of the gnolls to their knees, and as he spoke a light began to flow from the mouth of Malok, as a slow cry rose from deep within his soul.  In that moment, the light from Malok’s mouth joined with the swirling white swirls around the amulet.<p>
      The lich screamed with his mouth open, as if calling someone or something.  It was replied by the white lights flowing into his mouth, while some of the light remained and was sucked into the amulet once again.  The horrible scream turned from something unearthly to something more earthly, however still menacing.  Suddenly, the room darkened and the gnolls looked up from the floor at a robed man.  A man who was no longer dead and decaying.<p>
     All in the room were silent, except for a few stray whimpers.  Miragul was draped in a red robe, with streaks of blackish-blue running down the front, and tied at the waist.  Symbols on his robe pulsed with some magical energy.  He stood about six feet, and his appearance was more of a young Erudite man, not the old age that he had ‘died’ at.  A smile spread across his face, as he began to dust off his robe.  Looking up he saw Malok standing in front of him.<p>
     "I thank ye great dog for your sacrifice.  I had never thought dogs were capable of weaving spells of such art and power.  Ye have my thanks," with that Miragul pushed the right shoulder of the gnoll leader and watched it fall to the ground, it’s face contorted and lifeless.<p>
     The gnolls about the room took in breaths of air as they saw their leader fall.  He appeared to be drained of all life, even his eyes stared up hollow.  No blood was in body any longer, even his flesh was missing in areas, dried and crusted.  They eyed the tome that was still in the hands of Malok as Miragul knelt down to retrieve it.  Though, when his fingers touched it he uttered curses in an unknown tongue to them.  <p>
     "Bah!  What in the Ro’s fiery name is protecting that tome!"  Miragul shouted to the room, but knew he would receive no answer and grumbled to himself as he stood and just stared at the book.<p>
     "It is the Protection of Ro.  Used in a lesser effect, so it can be carried without setting anything it touches on fire.  If it were used to it’s full extent, it could fall through the ground burning it away," the metallic voice filled the air again, sending waves of pulsing throughout the crystal.<p>
     Miragul turned toward the sound, and eyed the crystal on the floor lying on a backpack before Barnok.  Raising an eyebrow, the mage looked up at Barnok and asked him a question in his own native tongue.			<p>
     "Was that ye, dog?"<p>
     Barnok shook his head, and pointed at the pulsating crystal.<p>
     Miragul’s eye brows raised again as his eyes went from Barnok to the crystal at his feet.  A flush of embarrassment went over him because he had never talked to a crystal before.  Not knowing how to begin, he simply referred back to the subject the ‘crystal’ was talking about.<p>
     "Protection of Ro?  There is no spell that bears that name, crystal."  Miragul claimed as he study the crystal intently, waiting for a reply.<p>
     "No spell that you know of, <i>mage</i>" came the metallic chiming reply.<p>
     Mirgaul almost jumped back at the sound, he had never seen a talking crystal.<p>
     "Profound!  How long have I been away that they’ve got crystals to talk and have spirits?!" At that, the mage began to walk about the room as if beginning to enter a deep thinking trance.<p>
     "No one made me talk.  I am a man trapped inside this crystal, and you, Miragul, are the only one who can help me out," the voice began to sound more hollow, in the metallic way.<p>
     Mirgaul stopped his pacing, and turned to look at the crystal.  "Me?"<p>
     "Yes, you’re the only one, <i>alive</i>, with enough skill within the art of necromancy to do such a thing, that I require."<p>
     "Well," the mage thought for a moment and then continued, "why are ye in a crystal, men are just not born into them, ye had to be put there for a reason," his voice ringed with a tint of an accusation.<p>
     "It was a spell that went bad, you of all people should know that is possible," the voice of the crystal sounded poisoned as it spoke those last words, and they made Miragul wince at the remembrance of his lich spell gone bad.<p>
     "Aye, I understand the feeling.  What then can I do to help ye?"<p>
     The mage walked over to the crystal and picked it up off the floor.  It’s touch was soothingly warm, yet seemed somehow cooled.  As it pulsed, waves of pleasure washed over the mage, who wasn’t too sure how to react to such a feeling, from a crystal.<p>
     "There was once an old tower within the lands of Erudin, I believe it lied more in the forests known as Toxxulia in modern labels.  It will most likely need to be raised from within the earth, but I shall provide you with the spell.  Inside this tower, on the first floor, there is an alter.  Here, is where this crystal must be put.<p>
     "In that tome, which I will explain on how you can decipher the symbols, there is a page in the back that describes the incantation.  This one, does not need a sacrifice, for my body was put into here whole, flesh and all.  After the incantation is completed, I’ll be able to thank you in my own fleshy person." pulsed out the crystal, it’s voice fluctuating.<p>
     "Well, if I help ye, what do I receive in return?" Miragul stroked the crystal feeling it’s smooth perfect edges.<p>
     "You will be able to declare the Tome of Diz’Urian as your own, and no longer will it burn to touch."<p>
      Miragul stood up straigh, in utter shock.  Then gave a scowl at the crystal.  "The Tome of Diz’Urian is a myth and legend!  It never existed, the Tome of Life was just a flashy title to entice young necromancers," the mage spoke while tightly grasping the crystal "no one had the power that those stories lay claim about the Tome."<p>
     The air filled with a metallic laughter, sending chills into all those present even the mage.  Many of the gnolls whimpered more, and stayed on the ground covering their heads.  This magic scared them, as did the horrible laughing sound piercing into their heads.<p>
     "Miragul, do not make me second guess my choice.  Do you really think that book does not exist," the tempo of the voice picked up, as if upset, "if it did not, then how do you explain your form being whole and younger again?  Yet, while keeping the old body and soul?  Explain to me, Miragul, how this can be achieved, oh great <i>lich</i>."<p>
     Miragul stood for a moment, contemplating the thought.  Then his eyes shifted towards the tome on the floor and he gasped.  The symbol on the cover was that of the Combine Empire, but it was altered with snakes streaming alongside it’s normal insignia.  And about the symbol, was an ancient looking rune, one that he had never seen before in all his years of arcane research and study.<p>
     "So, will you accept my offer?"<p>
     The mage nodded absently, as his eyes remained transfixed upon the tome as visions of grandeur and power filled his head.  "Yes, when can we leave?" his voice sounded distant, lost within an arcane dreamworld.<p>
     "Now, Miragul, now." growled out the metallic voice.		<p>	
<center>**********************************************<p></center>
	     As Simonic sat at a wooden table inside the Steel Warriors quarters,  Dorson and Camlend attended to Kinloc, who was found freezing within a large block of ice.  A fire burned quietly in the corner of the room, giving a gentle glow and warmth to the room.  Outside Karana’s rain poured on the fires, a rain caused by Truven, as Sim could tell by it’s markings.  Even though, he had not made an appearance to the group yet.<p>
     Ebon had left a few moments before to visit the Temple of Nife, and explain to the priests and priestesses there about their high priest.  Also, he figured he would check on Milor, a poor guy he had forgotten about during all the fighting and pain.  Tiethroe begged to come along, but Ebon refused.  Which, just caused the little half elf to follow him unknowing in his shadows.<p>
     Simonic tapped absently on the table, while occasionally rubbing his hand over the shaft of his staff.  His thoughts wandering from the gnolls, to the battle, and then to Miragul.  Something about the plan he had thought earlier didn’t seem to fit together.  The gnoll’s had no use for a lich.  They were fairly good in the arts themselves, and then the chances of Miragul aiding them in magic were very slim.  <p>
     Thoughts of how Miragul once was flooded into his head.  He was a man obsessed with finding out all there was to magic.  Going at great lengths to obtain ancient artifacts, even to the point of crypt robing.  It was this horde of artifacts that made him become fearful, and then enclosed himself within the peaks of EverFrost.  Away from all life.  Simonic had always thought it sad, that even away from all life he still wanted to live forever.  Coming out of his holes to gain more skill in the art of death, along with some stolen relics.<p>
     A sigh escaped his lungs.  Necromancy, the curse of the gods.  An area within the arcane that through most deities was forbidden, and only a few allowed such acts within their followers.  Innoruuk, Bertoxxulous, and Cazic-Thule.  It was this that brought about the down fall of the Combine Empire, a lust for power.  And the power that lied within evil was astounding, however not out right awe-inspiring power.  The Guardian’s, at their creation, were banned from practicing such evil arts.  However, the human’s knew of ways to outsmart the gods themselves.<p>
     Something many of the elder races didn’t dare attempt, and looked down upon.  Yet, the Guardian’s held extreme power within the realms and the elder races could not touch them.  Save for the dragons, being the brood of Veeshan.  Veeshan was left out of the pact that the gods made to create the Guardian race.  A balanced breed of beings, to offer protection the god’s no longer wished to give.  Their supposed <i>final</i> divine intervention.  Yet, for the elder races to attempt a negotiation with a dragon, often ended with one’s death.  So, nothing could be done to stop the Empire and their expansions.<p>
     It was due to this fear of their power, that they were accepted into almost any culture, except for those who served the dark gods openly.  Also, the fact that to kill a guardian took extreme power that very few, if any, mortals possessed.  Even the gods could not directly touch them any longer.  They reigned in almost complete power and force, force through magic granted to them by the highest gods.  Until, they brought themselves down.<p>
     "Simonic, are you alright?" Dorson asked as had left Kinloc in the corner who seemed to be sleeping well next to the fire.<p>
     Simonic smiled as he watched Dorson sit down across from him, "Aye, child," his eyes seemed to observe Dorson more, "just thinking about the events and the past."<p>
     Dorson’s eyes appeared to be looking into the distance as he thought of the events in the past day, and the grisly sights.  His stomach lurched.<p>
     "Don’t dwell on it too much Dorson, we can do nothing about the past, only expect things for the future, and hope for the best" the mage held out his hand and gently patted Dor’s arm reassuring him things would be ok, or so he hoped.<p>
     "Do you think Paineel will do well against the gnoll forces?" the young man’s face turned from one of thinking to one of concern, as he peered up at the mage.<p>
     "I’m not sure they plan to attack, if they do they would get fairly far, there are no wizards and the like within their accursed walls.  Yet, the place is busy with magic new and old."<p>
     "Sim, did the Combine Empire ever have any palaces over in Erudin?  I had always heard stories that Erud moved there in remembrance of the great wizards within the Empire," Dor continued, "and I know Miragul had once lived there, I had heard various druids tell cryptic stories of the man at the druid rings late at night.  Though, I don’t know how much of it was truth I was only a child then."<p>
     Realization hit Simonic and he shot up taking hold of his staff.  As he jolted up, Dorson did as well.<p>
     "What, what is it?" Dorson asked his mage friend.<p>
     "I must go, now." Simonic was already pacing toward the direction of the door, with silvery hair waving in his wake.<p>
     Dorson was on his trail, "wait, Sim I need to go with you."<p>
     Simonic halted and turned looking down at the druid with an eye brow cocked up.<p>
     "Why?" Was all the mage asked.<p>
     Dorson halted for a moment, and swallowed hard.  The sight the mage had just given him sent chills through his body, Simonic apparently noticed this as he let his expression soothe.  A little.<p>
     "Truven ordered me to stay with you, even if you turned me down.  I am to follow you," he had managed to speak out, however, slowly.<p>
     "When did you speak with Truven?" A small hint of suspicion or confusion hit the mage’s voice as he probed the druid with questions.<p>
     "I spoke with him outside the bank, before the rains had started, while I was sent out to get water for Kinloc," Dorson pointed out in the direction of the water pool where he retrieved the water.<p>
     "We spoke of the battle and then I showed him the Hall of Sorcery.  When he saw it, he casted the weather spell.  That’s why it took me so long, I had asked him if I could go with him, but he said he was going someplace I could not enter,<p>
     "I had mentioned your name to him, and he smiled.  He told me I was in great hands and said follow you everywhere and anywhere, regardless of what that <i>old man</i> says."  Dorson finished his recount of what had happened earlier, nervous that he had stepped on something he should not have.<p>
     At the mention of <i>old man</i> Simonic smiled, releasing some of the tension on himself and the young druid. A chuckle escaped his throat.<p>
     "Well, if old <i>hairy grey-feet</i> says you must come with me, then I guess I <i>better</i> take ya along," a smile spread across his face as he looked down at the druid.<p>
     "Where we goin?" Dorson asked.<p>
     Simonic’s hands were already in the motion of a spell, as stripes of thunder rang about the outside arena.  At the question, the mage just grinned.  Dorson didn’t know if he should be frightened or if he already knew.  As the spell completed, a large portal began to shimmer about them and began to pull at their persons, a small pang tugged at Dorson’s skin, who was un-accustomed to this form of travel.<p>
     "Toxxulia For--" the mage whispered before their forms and his words were sucked into the portal.<p>
     <center>**********************************************<p>
<b>Chapter Eight</b><br><i>The Tower. Gnolls. A Man.</i></center><p>
Miragul walked among the plant life, listening to the calls of the forests.  Calls he had not heard in ages, he still wondered how long he had been <i>dead</i> for.  And even while he was alive, he failed to capture nature preferring to live in solitaire, for various reasons.  At his sash, a gnoll had made a small leather holster for the crystal, as he and it talked occasionally.  As they walked, Branok stood beside Miragul, as the other gnolls walked behind them, letting the mage lead with the aid of the crystal.<p>
<center><b><i>...more to come...</b></i></center> </font></td>
